SPECIES COMMENTS: In slightly wet paddy. Very dark compared to Little Stint. Identical to Teeside bird [= first UK record] but duller plumage. Dark brown above with pale fringes. Streaks on sided of breast & neck more prominent [than on Little], with warm flush. Crown and cheeks v dark. Supercillium dusky but broad and prominent. Weak bill. Long legs and neck, round head, like a little Wood Sand - call 'joot - joot' singular or plural. V dark and slim long-winged in flight. Underwing looking dark. Also wing-bar very narrow. Picks food from surface, usually stretching upward when alert.

TRIP COMMENTS: With C Mohankumar, first time going to the sanctuary.. we walked some km into the forest towards the watch tower about 8 km away..At the bifurcation point we heard sawing-like sounds continuously and suspected it to be the mating call of the Leopard and retreated to Srambi.  The right hand route takes to the border of Mudumalai.  Full of Eucalyptus plantation...then teak plantation..Near the Srambi there were 50-60 Common Langurs in 4-5 groups..young ones also.  Bonnets, Barking Deers, Giant Squirrel etc.  Droppings of Sloth Bear found.

Bonnets, Barking Deers, Giant Squirrel etc.  Droppings of Sloth Bear found.

Johnsingh; M.D. Madhusudan; S. Quader; T.R.S. Raman; S.U. Saravanakumar.--Note: some species have count entered as zero. This is for comparison with a later Ganga count in 1995, available at this link.

From AVC College Men's Hostel. With Balan.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Heard quite a few birds chattering and causing a ruckus outside (I think Indian Roller and Black Drongo but not very sure since I had not mentioned it in my diary but vaguely remember these two birds though) then looked through my room window and saw this bird on a thickets in front of the hostel. Our room was on the first floor. Showed it to my room make Balan. The bird hopped inside the bush. Later we saw the bird in flight as well. Such an unmistakable and beautiful bird. ----I was in 2nd Year Masters in Wildlife biology then.

LOCALITY: Wetland along railway track near Guntakal
TRIP COMMENTS: Travelling back to Bangalore by train from Delhi on 30th January 1996, about 5 minute from Guntakal Junction in Andhra Pradesh towards Bangalore, just to the right besides the railway track  I came across a half-filled water reservoir. At the northern edge I saw about 6 'white' birds feeding. Fortunately for me, the train slowed down and stopped for reasons best known to its driver. I had enough time to take out my 12 x 50 binoculars and have a good look at them. I could confirm that they were white storks [Ciconia ciconia]. Also I had some time to look at other waterbirds which included a couple of hundred of Northern pintails [Anas acuta].
